tribunicia potestas. Sulla (no. 82-79) had sought to limit the authority of the tribunes of the plebs by placing considerable restrictions on their right of addressing the people whenever they thought fit, and by practically annulling their power of veto on any measure proposed by a magistrate by imposing a heavy fine on the abuse of this right. He had also enacted that no tribune of the plebs should be eligible for other magistracies (Mommsen, iii. p. 363). These restrictions had been lately removed in B.c. 70 in the consulship of Crassus and Pompeius.
